title: Open-Label Extension for Alzheimer's Disease Patients Who Complete One of Two Semagacestat Phase 3 Double-Blind Studies (H6L-MC-LFAN or H6L-MC-LFBC)
description_brief:
The primary objective of the original study was to assess the safety of semagacestat in Alzheimer's disease (AD) patients during 24 months of open-label treatment. Baseline for the efficacy measures is defined as the baseline for feeder studies LFAN (NCT00594568) and LFBC (NCT00762411). For all safety analyses (adverse events), baseline for patients will be week 0 of this study (LFBF).

Preliminary results from LFAN and LFBC showed semagacestat did not slow disease progression and was associated with worsening of clinical measures of cognition and the ability to perform activities of daily living. Study drug was stopped in all studies. Studies LFAN, LFBC and LFBF have been amended to continue collecting safety data, including cognitive scores, for at least seven months. The CT-Registry will reflect results of analyses from the original protocol in addition to those from the amended protocol. Very few participants from LFBC rolled over into LFBF (N = 9). Due to insufficient sample size, the data for LFBC participants who rolled into LFBF were not analyzed.

measures.title: Alzheimer's Disease Assessment Scale - Cognitive Subscale (ADAS-Cog11)
measures.description: The cognitive subscale of the ADAS (ADAS-Cog11) was used as a primary efficacy measure and consisted of 11 items assessing areas of function most typically impaired in AD: orientation, verbal memory, language, and praxis. The scale ranged from 0-70, with higher scores indicating greater disease severity.

measures.title: Alzheimer's Disease Cooperative Study Activities of Daily Living Inventory (ADCS-ADL)
measures.description: The ADCS-ADL was a 23-item inventory developed as a rater-administered questionnaire answered by the participant's caregiver. It measures both basic and instrumental activities of daily living. The total ADCS-ADL score ranged from 0-78, with lower scores indicating greater disease severity.

outcomeMeasures.title: Change From Baseline in Clinical Dementia Rating Scale (Sum of Boxes) (CDR-SB) at Week 24
outcomeMeasures.description: The CDR-SB is a semi-structured interview of participants and their caregivers. The participant's cognitive status is rated in 6 domains of functioning, including memory, orientation, judgment and problem solving, community affairs, home and hobbies, and personal care. A severity score is assigned for each of the 6 domains with total score ranging from 0 to 18. Higher scores indicate greater disease severity. Least Square (LS) Mean value was controlled for baseline value, age, investigator, and concomitant standard of care (SOC) medication.

drug: semagacestat (LY450139) — oral gamma‑secretase inhibitor, small molecule
explanation_target: Reason: The intervention is semagacestat, an oral small‑molecule gamma‑secretase inhibitor intended to reduce production of amyloid‑β and thereby modify AD pathology (disease‑targeting mechanism). citeturn0search0turn0search2

Act: The phase‑3 programs (and open‑label extension described) were halted because semagacestat did not slow disease progression and was associated with worse cognition and functional outcomes; these findings and the drug's mechanism are reported by Eli Lilly and in peer‑reviewed publications. Based on that, the trial and drug match the 'disease‑targeted small molecule' category. citeturn0search0turn0search2turn0search1

Reflect: Classification check — semagacestat is not a biologic (it's a small molecule enzyme inhibitor), its intent was disease modification via lowering amyloid production rather than being a symptomatic cognitive enhancer or an agent for neuropsychiatric symptoms, and the study described is an extension/safety follow‑up of a disease‑targeting drug, so 'disease‑targeted small molecule' is appropriate. No placebo is listed for the open‑label extension (placebo array left empty). citeturn0search2turn0search3
explanation_agent: Reason: The investigational drug semagacestat (LY450139) is an oral small‑molecule gamma‑secretase inhibitor whose intended mechanism was to reduce production of amyloid‑β peptides (Aβ) and thereby modify AD pathology. citeturn0search0turn0search5

Act: The trial/drug therefore maps to CADRO category A) Amyloid beta because the intervention directly targets the enzyme (γ‑secretase) responsible for generating Aβ from APP. Phase‑3 programs and the open‑label extension were halted/modified after interim data showed no clinical benefit and signals of worse cognition and safety concerns — supporting that the intervention was disease‑targeting toward amyloid production. citeturn0search1turn0search2

Reflect: Semagacestat is a small‑molecule enzyme inhibitor (not a biologic) with primary intent to lower Aβ production; although γ‑secretase inhibition can affect other substrates (e.g., Notch) and produce off‑target effects, the principal target pathway is amyloid‑beta generation, so the most specific CADRO match is A) Amyloid beta. Missing information: none needed to assign category given the explicit mechanism. citeturn0search5turn0search1

Web search results (sources used): 1) Eli Lilly press release describing semagacestat as a γ‑secretase inhibitor intended to reduce Aβ and announcing halting of development after phase‑3 interim results. citeturn0search0 2) NEJM phase‑3 publication reporting semagacestat did not improve cognition, was associated with worse functional outcomes and more adverse events. citeturn0search1 3) Lilly follow‑up summary of post‑dosing data and the open‑label extension / follow‑up activities. citeturn0search2 4) PubMed/phase‑2 biomarker work showing LY450139 (semagacestat) biochemical effects consistent with γ‑secretase inhibition. citeturn0search3
